#compdef uniffi-bindgen
# =============================================================================
# uniffi-bindgen — Mozilla's "multi-language bindings generator for
#                  Rust" CLI — a code generator that takes UniFFI
#                  Definition Language (UDL) files or compiled Rust
#                  cdylib libraries and emits idiomatic foreign-
#                  language bindings for Kotlin, Swift, Python, and
#                  Ruby.  Originally developed for Firefox to enable
#                  cross-platform Rust code reuse on iOS + Android
#                  + Desktop + WebExtensions.  Distinguishing from
#                  cbindgen (C/C++ bindings), bindgen (Rust-from-C
#                  bindings), wasm-bindgen (WASM bindings), and
#                  napi-rs (Node.js bindings) by:
#                    - 4-LANGUAGE TARGET MATRIX: --language flag
#                      accepts kotlin/swift/python/ruby; can be
#                      specified multiple times to emit bindings
#                      for several languages in one invocation
#                    - UDL OR cdylib SOURCE INPUT: traditional UDL
#                      (Component Definition Language) files OR
#                      compiled Rust cdylib .so/.dll/.dylib files
#                      via --library mode (the modern default)
#                    - PIPELINE INSPECTION via `uniffi-bindgen
#                      pipeline` — debug the bindings-render
#                      pipeline; show specific pass output, type
#                      filter, name filter, diff vs no-diff
#                    - SCAFFOLDING GENERATION via `uniffi-bindgen
#                      scaffolding` — generate the Rust-side
#                      scaffolding code that exposes the FFI
#                      surface to foreign languages
#                    - GLOBAL CONFIG FILE via -c/--config —
#                      uniffi.toml with [defaults]/[crates.<name>]/
#                      [crate-roots] sections enabling per-crate
#                      override of binding options
#                    - cargo_metadata INTEGRATION via --metadata-
#                      no-deps for environments where Cargo
#                      sub-dependency resolution causes problems
#                    - FIREFOX-ECOSYSTEM PRODUCTION USE — UniFFI
#                      powers Firefox's sync, accounts, push,
#                      autofill, and other cross-platform Rust
#                      libraries that ship to iOS, Android,
#                      Desktop, and WebExtensions
#                  Used by: Mozilla teams + 3rd-party Rust library
#                  authors wanting to expose Rust APIs to mobile
#                  (Swift/Kotlin) + scripting (Python/Ruby) without
#                  hand-writing FFI bindings per platform.
#
# Author:  Mozilla (mozilla organization on GitHub) — originally
#          developed by the Application Services team at Mozilla
#          (the team behind Firefox Sync + Accounts + Push) starting
#          ~2020.  Continuously developed with weekly releases.
#          License: MPL-2.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/mozilla/uniffi-rs
#          https://github.com/mozilla/uniffi-rs/blob/main/uniffi/src/cli/uniffi_bindgen.rs
#          https://github.com/mozilla/uniffi-rs/blob/main/uniffi/uniffi-bindgen.rs
#          https://mozilla.github.io/uniffi-rs/ (documentation)
# CLI:     uniffi/src/cli/uniffi_bindgen.rs — uses clap 4.x derive
#          (`#[derive(Parser, Subcommand, Args, ValueEnum)]`) with
#          3 subcommands and per-subcommand flag sets.  Headline
#          library: **camino** (clap is well-documented across many
#          Rust completions; camino is the new variant being
#          documented here, opening Axis 14).
# Library: camino (https://github.com/camino-rs/camino)
#          ("camino" — Rain Paharia (camino-rs org) + David Tolnay
#           (dtolnay on GitHub, also author of serde + anyhow R598
#           + thiserror R602) — released 2020 as "Like Rust's std::
#           path::Path, but UTF-8".  Distinct from every previously-
#           documented Rust library by being narrowly focused on
#           UTF-8 PATH HANDLING in a Rust ecosystem that otherwise
#           treats paths as OS-specific byte strings (which may not
#           be UTF-8 on Linux/Unix where paths are arbitrary bytes
#           and on Windows where paths are UTF-16):
#             1. Utf8PathBuf + Utf8Path — drop-in replacements for
#                std::path::PathBuf + std::path::Path that GUARANTEE
#                UTF-8 ENCODING at the type level.  Converting from
#                an OS path requires explicit validation; converting
#                FROM camino back to std is infallible
#             2. METHOD-BY-METHOD API PARALLEL with std::path —
#                Utf8Path implements .as_str() / .file_name() /
#                .parent() / .join() / .with_extension() / .read_
#                dir() / .canonicalize() / etc. — every std::path
#                method mirrored with UTF-8 return types where
#                applicable
#             3. SERDE INTEGRATION via the "serde" feature — Utf8
#                PathBuf serializes/deserializes as String, unlike
#                std::path::PathBuf which uses awkward
#                OsString-wrapped representations
#             4. CARGO-DEPENDENCY — cargo (the Rust package manager)
#                uses camino internally for all path handling
#                because cargo manifests + lockfiles + index entries
#                are guaranteed UTF-8
#             5. ZERO-COST CONVERSION — Utf8Path::from_path(p) and
#                p.as_ref() are O(1) operations that simply validate
#                UTF-8 at runtime; no allocation
#             6. DAVID-TOLNAY ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — David Tolnay
#                co-maintains camino + serde + anyhow + thiserror
#                + syn + quote + proc-macro2; camino joins the
#                Tolnay infrastructure-Rust crate family
#             7. JSON/TOML/YAML CONFIG-COMPATIBLE — when round-
#                tripping configuration through serde-driven
#                config-rs (R629) or figment (R633), Utf8PathBuf
#                produces clean string output instead of OsString
#                quirks)
# License: MPL-2.0 (uniffi-rs); MIT OR Apache-2.0 (camino)
# Status:  uniffi-rs — 4,644+ stars on mozilla/uniffi-rs, production-
#          deployed in Firefox + Firefox Sync + 100+ Mozilla-
#          adjacent projects; camino — 556+ stars on camino-rs/
#          camino, ~150M crates.io downloads, foundational
#          dependency of cargo (THE Rust package manager — used
#          internally for all manifest path handling) + casey/just
#          (34k stars) + ankitects/anki (28k stars) + vercel/
#          turborepo + facet-rs/facet (2.5k stars) + microsoft/
#          windows-drivers-rs (1.9k stars) + foresterre/cargo-msrv
#          + coreos/rpm-ostree + mozilla/uniffi-rs (THIS) +
#          oxidecomputer/qorb + winglang/wing (already documented)
#          + 1500+ Rust applications needing UTF-8 path guarantees.
#
